The United States and Turkey signeda five-year defence and economic agreement (DECA) that willchannel hundreds of millions of dollars a year in aid toAnkara.    The agreement was signed by Secretary of State GeorgeShultz and Foreign Minister Vahit Halefoglu after 18 months ofnegotiations that won Ankara considerably less than it wanted.    Under the agreement, the U.S. government pledged it woulduse "vigor and determination" to persuade Congress to vote themoney to build up Turkish defenses in return for U.S. air basesand intelligence-gathering facilities.    Under today's agreement, which runs until December, 1990,Turkey will receive nearly 720 mln dlrs in military andeconomic aid this year.    Next year, the U.S. government has promised to ask Congressfor 910 mln dlrs under an agreement that prompted domesticcrticism in Turkey for not winning enough aid. Reuter&#3;